Problem 1: Gas Station

Theory A

Claim: This theory states, “Gas stations charge more if they lack direct competition in sight”.

Evidence: The box plots below display the relationship of if a gas station has a competitor or not, and its price.

name lower upper level method estimate
diffmean -0.0553414 0.0083284 0.95 percentile -0.0234824

Based on the box plot gas stations with no competitors have a larger range of prices and has a higher average price than that of gas stations with competitors. The claim of the theory that Gas stations charge more if they lack direct competition in sight”, proves correct. The difference of means is about -.023, which means that the mean is less than the hypothesized mean. Also above there is a bootstrapped histogram displayed containing a bootstrapped sample of price by competition, displaying the difference of means. The difference between gas station prices that have competitors and don’t is somewhere between -0.055 and 0.008, with 95% confidence.

Conclusion: Based on the data above the claim that “Gas stations charge more if they lack direct competition in sight” is supported.

Problem 3: NBC Network Shows

Part A

Question: The question I am trying to answer is, if there is evidence that one show consistently produces a higher mean for Question 1- Happy response among its viewers.

Approach: To answer this question I used the confint function and performed a 95 % confidence interval to find evidence for viewer response regarding the shows “Living with Ed” and “My name is Earl”.

Results:

name lower upper level method estimate
diffmean -0.3951221 0.1050476 0.95 percentile -0.1490515

In order to answer the question I made a table displaying the confidence interval data for difference of means and also made a bar graph to display the averages for both shows.

Conclusion To conclude there is no significant evidence to show that one show consistently produces a higher mean. The estimated means are very close and when running a 95% confidence interval somewhere between -0.40 and .11. Because of the interval and the true mean lying somewhere in between the two numbers further investigation between the two shows would have to be conducted.

Part B

Question: The question that needs to be answered is which reality/ contest show (“The Biggest Loser” and “The Apprentice: Los Angeles”) made people feel more annoyed, and is there evidence that show one show consistently producing a higher mean in the Q1_Annoyed response among viewers.

Approach: For this question i will use the function confint to for find the confidence interval as well as bootstrap a sample. I will construct this by filtering a data set that only contains “The Biggest Loser” and “The Apprentice: Los Angeles”.

Results:
name lower upper level method estimate
diffmean -0.5186703 -0.0217746 0.95 percentile -0.270997

These results provide a table that shows a 95% confidence interval for the difference in means for the shows “The Biggest Loser” and “The Apprentice: Los Angeles” after running a bootstrap.

Conclusion To conclude because the 95% confidence interval is between -0.52 and -0.02 there is statistical significance because the value of zero is not between these two numbers. Meaning that one show consistently produces more annoyance than the other. To answer the question of which show , “The Apprentice: Los Angeles” had the higher mean for the show being considered annoying. Therefore, this show may not be a hit with viewers.

Part C

Question: The question is what proportion of American TV watchers would we expect to give a response 4 or greater to the “Q2_Confusing” question for the show “Dancing With the Stars”.

Approach: For this question I will use confint to find the confidence interval of proportions and by constructing a confidence interval by bootstrapping the DWTS (Dancing With The Stars) filtered data it should help answer the question.

Results:

Based on calculations for the proportion confidence interval or the response of 4 or greater to the Q2_Confusing question my approach provided me with statistical certainty evidence for the question.

Conclusion To conclude after constructing a 95% confidence interval there is statically significant evidence that the true proportion of American TV watchers of DWTS that gave a response of 4 or greater to the “Q2_Confusing” is between 0.04 and 0.12. Because zero is not included in this interval we can conclude statistical significance.

Problem 4: EBay

Question: The question that needs to be answered is, “…assess the evidence for whether the revenue ratio is the same in the treatment and control groups, or whether instead the data favors the idea that paid search advertising on Google creates extra revenue for EBay”.

Approach: In order to answer this question the statistical approach used was constructing a confidence interval, by bootstrapping.

Results:

The evidence or results my approach provided in the table above was a 95% confidence interval for the question provided.

Conclusion: Based on the 95% confidence interval between -0.09 and -0.01 there is statistical evidence that the data favors the idea that paid search advertising on Google creates revenue for Ebay.
